split-parts on the providers are also preloaded to their memory. On each service provider, three threads are running parallel to implement computation, data receiving, and data transmission by sharing data with a queue. All the codes are implemented in Python3. We mainly focus on the optimal distribution of the convolutional layers and maxpooling layers in this paper. The last fully-connected layer(s) are computed on the service provider with the highest allocated amount of the last layervolume in our experiments.

B. Baseline Methods
To evaluate the performance of DistrEdge compared to state-of-the-art CNN inference distribution methods, we take seven methods as our baseline: (1) CoEdge [63] (linear models for devices and networks, layer-by-layer split); (2) MoDNN [36] (linear models for devices, layer-by-layer split); (3) MeDNN [37] (linear models for devices, layer-by-layer split); (4) DeepThings [68] (equal-split, one fused-layers); (5) DeeperThings [53] (equal-split, multiple fused-layers); (6) AOFL [69] (linear models for devices and networks, multiple fused layers); (7) OfÔ¨Çoad: We select the service provider with the best computing hardware (e.g., the best GPU) to ofÔ¨Çoad the CNN inference. Note that equal-split refers to splitting layer(s) equally (DeepThings and DeeperThings). In contrast, CoEdge, AOFL, MoDNN, and MeDNN split layer(s) based on linear models of computation and/or transmission. Layer-by-layer refers to making split decisions per layer (CoEdge, MoDNN, and MeDNN). One fused-layer refers to fusing multiple layers once in a CNN model (DeepThings). Multiple fused-layers refer to allowing more than one fused-layers in a CNN model (DeeperThings and AOFL). The term fused-layer is equivalent to layer-volume in DistrEdge.
C. Œ± and |Rrs| in LC-PSS We Ô¨Årst study the effect of the hyper-parameter Œ± and |Rrs|
in LC-PSS (Algorithm 1), as shown in Fig. 5 and 6. Œ± controls the trade-off between O and T when calculating
Cp (Eq. 3). We observe that, when Œ± is smaller, LC-PSS tends

to partition the CNN model into more layer-volumes, and vice versa. For example, VGG-16 is partitioned into 16 layervolumes with Œ± = 0 and is partitioned into only two layervolumes with Œ± = 1. To observe the overall performance with different Œ±, we further run the OSDS (Algorithm 2) with the partition schemes obtained with Œ± = {0, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1.0} under four types of environments for VGG-16 inference: (1) We have four homogeneous service providers under 200Mbps WiFi; (2) The service providers‚Äô types are heterogeneous (Group DB in Table I); (3) The service providers‚Äô WiFi bandwidths are heterogeneous (Group NA in Table II); (4) We have 16 service (Group LB, LC, LD in Table III). The performance comparison is shown in Fig. 5 (a) to (d). We can observe poor performance with Œ± = 0 (Cp is only affected by the number of operations) and Œ± = 1 (Cp is only affected by the amount of transmission data). The highest performance is achieved with Œ± = 0.75 in all cases. Overall, we should consider both the number of operations and the amount of transmission data when searching for the optimal partition scheme. We set Œ± = 0.75 in the rest of our experiments. This study also shows that distribution CNN model layer-bylayer [63, 36, 37] is not efÔ¨Åcient (e.g., Œ± = 0).

