|Rrs| is the number of random split decisions in Eq. 4. It affects the averaged score C¬Øp in Algorithm 1 (line 8). With a small |Rrs|, the optimal partition locations generated
by LC-PSS can change signiÔ¨Åcantly, as different groups of random split decisions lead to different C¬Øp. With a large |Rrs|, the optimal partition locations generated by LC-PSS
does not show much difference, as different groups of random split decisions lead to similar C¬Øp. We compare the overall performance (IPS) with different |Rrs| in two cases (Group-
DB with 50Mbps WiFi and Group-NA with Nano), as shown in Fig 6. For each |Rrs| value, we repeatedly run LC-PSS 50
times and record the optimal partition locations of each time. We aggregate the IPS performance over 50 times for each |Rrs|
value in Fig. 6, and the maximum, average, and minimum IPS among 50 results are shown. When |Rrs| is small (e.g., 25 and 50), the IPS varies in a wide range. When |Rrs| is large (larger than or equal to 100), the IPS keeps stable. Thus, we set |Rrs| to 100 in the rest of our tests.

